The paper proposes a novel learning scheme for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to reduce their computational cost without compromising accuracy. This is a common problem in computer vision, which falls under the category of computer science (cs). The paper specifically focuses on deep learning and CNNs, which are subfields of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The proposed method involves pruning insignificant channels in the network, which is a technique used to reduce the size and complexity of neural networks (cs.NE). The paper also evaluates the effectiveness of the proposed method on image classification datasets, which is a common task in computer vision (cs.CV). Finally, the paper does not explicitly mention natural language processing, but the proposed method could potentially be applied to text classification tasks, which fall under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL).
